# Removing waves from the gravity current PIV data

## Editorial

The work for this chapter is completely done. I need to extend and
refine the words below but the bulk of it is there. I'd estimate a
further couple of drafts to finish this off, each taking a day.

The work here is me solving the biggest blocking problem in getting
to analyse the rest of the data. As you'll see, the waves in the
data were very obvious in any frequency analysis.

Each time I thought I had the problem solved I came across some
additional feature of the waves that I hadn't accounted for.
This happened for each of

- the shallow water approximation not holding
- the horizontal variation of standing waves
- the vertical profile varying strongly with frequency
- the waves decaying with time

Realising the waves were not a PIV processing artefact and were
standing waves (and therefore controllable) was frustrating. This
problem was likely avoidable experimentally and demonstrates nicely
what can happen when performing lab work under excess time pressure.

All runs are contaminated with background waves. We can remove high
frequency waves from all runs; however, lower frequency waves can
only be removed from runs with a long measurement period prior to
the front passage. Not knowing this, when doing the experiments I
cut down the majority of the runs to include only a short period
before the front passage (to save disk space). This leaves us with 5
runs that can be wave-subtracted :(


## Overview

As discussed previously, we are going to look at our gravity current
velocity data in a frame of reference moving with the current front
(the GC frame).

All velocity data is transformed from the LAB frame into the GC
frame, in which the position of the gravity current front is
stationary. In the GC coordinate system (z, t, t') we can easily
compute a mean current field, along a single axis.

@fig:mean-field shows the mean of the data in the GC frame. This
mean looks as we might expect - like a gravity current in cross
section, with a raised head followed by shear induced billows.

```{.python .input  n=3}
## fig:mean-field
# The the mean streamwise velocity in the gravity current frame.
# Higher frequency standing waves average out to zero in this frame.
##

mean = np.mean(r.transformer.to_front(r.U[...]), axis=1)
zf, tf = r.Z[:, 0, 3500:8000], r.T[:, 0, 3500:8000]

u_levels= np.linspace(-0.05, 0.1, 200)

plt.contourf(tf, zf, mean[..., 3500:8000], levels=u_levels)
plt.colorbar();
```

@fig:single-slice shows the state of the gravity current at a single
point in its evolution. Clearly the data is overlaid by a wave like
signal.

```{.python .input  n=4}
## fig:single-slice
# Streamwise velocity over $(z, t)$ as recorded by a single column
# in the PIV grid. The gravity current signal is clearly modulated
# by a periodic signal that is coherent over the full depth of the
# fluid.
##

plt.contourf(r.t, r.z, r.U[:, 20, :], levels=u_levels)

plt.title('streamwise velocity (m / s)')
plt.ylabel('vertical (m)')
plt.xlabel('time (s)');
```

The waves are present throughout the time series and well before the
front passage.

If we can isolate the wave signal then, assuming superposition, we
can recover the waveless signal.

Consider the power spectrum of the velocity prior to the current
onset, shown in @fig:presignal-fft.

There are several wave frequencies represented: there apears to be a
harmonic series beginning at ~0.1Hz, along with a cluster of
frequencies around 1Hz.

```{.python .input  n=5}
## fig:presignal-fft
# Power spectrum of streamwise velocity prior to front passage.
##

presignal = r.U[-1, 0, :3000]

fft = np.fft.rfft(presignal)
freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(presignal.size, d=0.01)

plt.semilogx(freqs, np.abs(fft))
plt.xlabel('frequency')
plt.ylabel('power')
plt.title('power spectrum')

fmin = 1 / (r.t[:3000].max() - r.t[:3000].min())
fmax = 100 / 2
plt.xlim(fmin, fmax);
```

We will focus now on the harmonic series of frequencies that appears
in the power spectrum.

One hypothesis for the cause of the frequency peaks is standing
waves in the tank. These could emerge from a number of sources.

The tank is filled with a hose at one end of the tank. In the single
layer runs examined here this is done at high speed. The
overpressure at the hose inlet would be a sufficient perturbation to
excite a series of standing waves.

Another potential source of the waves is the lock release itself; in
a tank with a free surface we expect a surface wave mode [@baines1995].

Since we did not control for the source of the waves (e.g with
baffles, filling the tank very slowly) we cannot be sure of the
source of them but we will focus here on the assumption that they
are standing waves.

The phase velocity of linear waves in shallow water $c_p$ is given by

$$
c_p = \sqrt{gH}
$$

The frequencies of standing waves are given by

$$
f_n = \frac{n c_p}{2L}
$$

for integer $n$ (as the waves must have nodes at the ends of the
tank due to the $u=0$ boundary condition.

The full length of the tank is $L = 5.50 \pm{0.005} \mathrm{m}$ and
the height $H = 0.25 \pm{0.005} \mathrm{m}$, giving a base standing
wave frequency of $f_1 = 0.142 \pm{0.001} \mathrm{Hz}$.

```{.python .input  n=6}
f1 = 0.142
shallow_frequencies = f1 * np.arange(1, 4)

def plot_shallow_frequencies(f1=f1, n=4):
    for n in range(1, n + 1):
        plt.axvline(n * f1, color='k')

fmin = 1 / (r.T[:].max() - r.T[:].min())
fmax = 0.5 / r.dt
```

#### Frequency resolution in the power spectrum

We can increase the quality of our power spectrum, at least for the
harmonic series, by increasing the frequency resolution and by using
a more appropriate windowing function on our signal.

Padding the signal with several times its length of zeros will
increase the frequency resolution.

An appropriate windowing function will minimise spectral leakage
from the frequency components that make up the signal.

We have implicitly used a uniform rectangular (boxcar) window, which
has a non monotonic (sinc) frequency representation, leading to
spurious peaks to the sides of real ones. A more appropriate choice
would be a Hanning window, which has smoothly decreasing side lobes
in frequency.

Our improved power spectrum is shown in @fig:extended-power.

```{.python .input  n=7}
## fig:extended-power-shallow
# Windowed and extended power spectrum of streamwise velocity
# prior to front passage. Shallow water standing wave frequencies
# for n < 5 are overlaid.
##

def plot_smooth_fft(signal, **kwargs):
    window = kwargs.pop('window', 'hanning')
    size = kwargs.pop('size', 2**15)
    xlim = kwargs.pop('xlim', (0.05, 2.5))
    ylim = kwargs.pop('ylim', (0, 5))
    ax = kwargs.pop('ax', None) or plt.gca()
    
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.size, fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, size)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    power = np.abs(fft)
    
    ax.semilogx(freqs, power, **kwargs)

    ax.set_xlim(*xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(*ylim)


plot_smooth_fft(presignal)
plot_shallow_frequencies()
plt.title('power spectrum (windowed and extended)')
plt.xlabel('frequency')
plt.ylabel('power');
```

## Problem Characterisation

### Frequency agreement

@fig:extended-power-shallow shows close agreement between the predicted
standing wave frequencies and the observed peaks, however there is
an increasing discrepancy at higher frequencies. The cause of this
discrepancy is the diminishing validity of the shallow water
approximation.

The full dispersion relation for two dimensional water waves is

$$
w^2 = g k \tanh(k H)
$$

and the condition for standing waves is given by

$$
k = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda} = \frac{n \pi}{L}
$$

Using this relation we get a much improved match between the observed and
predicted peak locations, as shown in @fig:extended-power-standing.

```{.python .input  n=8}
## fig:extended-power-standing
# Extended and windowed power spectrum of streamwise velocity.
# Standing wave frequencies using the full dispersion relation
# are overlaid. The full dispersion relation is necessary to find
# the frequencies of higher order standing waves as the shallow
# water approximation loses validity.
##

L = 5.50
H = 0.25
g = 9.81

def kn(n):
    return np.pi * n / L

def standing_frequency(n=None, k=None, scaling=1.006):
    if n is None and k is None:
        return
    elif k is None:
        k = kn(n)
    w2 = g * k * np.tanh(k * H)
    return scaling * np.sqrt(w2) / (2 * np.pi)

def plot_standing_frequencies(n=4, scaling=1.008, color='k', alpha=0.4, **kwargs):
    scaling = kwargs.pop('scaling', 1.008)
    ax = kwargs.pop('ax', None) or plt.gca()
    for i in range(n):
        ax.axvline(standing_frequency(i + 1, scaling=scaling), color=color, alpha=alpha, **kwargs)

plot_smooth_fft(presignal, window='hanning')
plot_standing_frequencies(30)

plt.xscale('linear')
plt.xlim(0.01, 2.5)
plt.ylim(0, 2);
```

@fig:extended-power-standing suggests that the vast majority of the observed
power in the pre-current signal originates from standing waves.

### Resolution of distinct frequency peaks {#sec:peak-isolation}

At higher frequencies it becomes increasingly difficult to resolve the peaks.
@harris1978 gives the resolution bandwidth of a single spectral line (using a
6.0dB drop from the peak) for several window functions in @table:window-
bandwidth.
A pair of equal amplitude peaks must be separated by at least this
bandwidth if they are to be resolved. Unequal peaks may require a
significantly larger separation.


| Window     | resolution bandwidth (6dB)  |
|------------|-----------------------------|
| Boxcar     | 1.2  |
| Hamming    | 1.81 |
| Hanning    | 1.65 |
| Blackman   | 2.35 |

Table: Resolution bandwidth for several different windowing functions
{#table:window-bandwidth}

where a bin is $\omega_s / N$ for the sampling frequency $\omega_s$ and the
number of samples $N$.

```{.python .input  n=9}
plot_smooth_fft(presignal, window='boxcar')
plot_standing_frequencies(30)

plt.xscale('linear')
plt.xlim(0.01, 2.5)
```

```{.python .input  n=10}
## fig:window-bandwidth
# Frequency resolution bandwidth as a function of frequency.
# As frequency increases, the gap between sucessive standing waves
# decreases. The resolution limits for various window functions
# and signal lengths are shown.
##

N = np.arange(1, 60)
W = standing_frequency(N)

plt.plot(W, np.gradient(W))

plt.title(r'-6.0dB frequency resolution bandwidth $\Delta f(f)$')
plt.ylabel('bandwidth, $\Delta f$')
plt.xlabel('frequency, $f$')

plot_standing_frequencies(60, color='k', alpha=0.2)

window_resolutions = [('boxcar pre', 1.2 * 100 / 3000),
                      ('boxcar full', 1.2 * 100 / 8000),
                      ('hanning pre', 1.65 * 100 / 3000),
                      ('hanning full', 1.65 * 100 / 8000),
                      ('blackman pre', 2.35 * 100 / 3000),
                      ('blackman full', 2.35 * 100 / 8000)
                     ]

for win, res in window_resolutions:
    plt.axhline(res, color='k')
    
wins, ress = zip(*window_resolutions)
ax = plt.twinx()
ax.set_ylim(0, 0.14)
ax.set_yticks(ress)
ax.set_yticklabels(['{:.3f} ({})'.format(res, win) for win, res in window_resolutions])

plt.xlim(0, 3);
```

Using the full signal (pre and post front) improves peak resolution
at the expense of contaminatination with a broad background of
frequency components.

This background is most problematic at lower frequencies, certainly
for the first three modes (see @fig:fft-mean-mean).

```{.python .input  n=11}
## fig:fft-mean-mean
# Power spectrum of the full signal (including the gravity current),
# averaged over both horizontal and vertical.
# The increased number of data points allows for clearer peak separation
# up to higher frequencies. However, at low frequencies the spectrum is
# clearly altered by gravity current signal that survives the averaging
# process.
##

plot_smooth_fft(r.U[:, :, :8000].mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0))
#plt.yscale('log')
plt.xscale('linear')
plt.xlim(0.01, 3)
plt.ylim(0, 6)

plot_standing_frequencies(400);
```

### Transition frequency of coherent features {#sec:fcrit}

As we can see in @fig-fft-mean-mean, lower frequency features do not average out
to have non zero power. We can approximate a frequency below which we expect
this to occur as the front speed divided by the observation window width. This
approximate transition frequency is shown in @fig:fft-fcrit. At all frequencies,
features with constant phase (i.e. standing waves) do not average out to zero
power. Incoherent features only average out to zero power at higher frequencies.

```{.python .input  n=12}
def critical_frequency(r):
    """Calculate the frequency below which we expect periodic features
    to not be averaged out by mean subtraction.
    """
    c = r.front_speed
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    fcrit = c / (x.max() - x.min())
    return fcrit

fcrit = critical_frequency(r)
```

```{.python .input  n=13}
def contour_fft(signal, axis=-1, size=2**15, window='hanning', xlim=(0.05, 2.5), levels=(0, 1, 50), ax=None):
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.shape[axis], fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, size, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
        
    lvl = np.linspace(*levels)
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    Ff, Xf = np.meshgrid(freqs, x)

    which = (freqs > xlim[0]) & (freqs < xlim[1])
    F = Ff[:, which]
    X = Xf[:, which]
     
    return ax.contourf(F, X, np.abs(fft)[:, which], levels=lvl)
    
def plot_total_fft(signal, xlim=(0.01, 3), ylim=(0, 10), window='hanning', size=2**15, ax=None):
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.shape[-1], fftbins=False)

    rfft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, n=size, axis=-1)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)

    ax.plot(freqs, np.abs(rfft).mean(axis=0))
    ax.set_xlim(*xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(*ylim)
```

```{.python .input  n=17}
## fig:fft-fcrit
# Power spectra of the full signal showing the location 
# of the estimated transition frequency (c / X).
# Above the transition frequency, features approximately
# average out to zero power unless they have constant phase.
##

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True)

plot_smooth_fft(r.U[-60].mean(axis=0), ax=ax[0], xlim=(0.05, 2.5))
ax[0].set_xscale('linear')

contour_fft(r.U[-60], levels=(0, 5), ax=ax[1], xlim=(0.05, 2.5))

ax[0].set_title('(a) power spectrum of the full signal averaged over $(x, z)$')
ax[1].set_title('(b) power spectrum of the full signal averaged over $z$')

ax[0].axvline(fcrit, ymin=-1, ymax=1, clip_on=False, color='red', linewidth=2)
ax[1].axvline(fcrit, color='red', linewidth=2)

ax[0].set_ylabel('amplitude')

ax[1].set_xlabel('frequency (Hz)')
ax[1].set_ylabel('horizontal (m)')

ax[0].annotate('| transition frequency', xy=(fcrit, 3), xytext=(fcrit + 0.05, 4));
```

### Removal strategy

As described in @sec:peak-isolation, it becomes very difficult to
identify distinct frequency peaks at higher frequencies.

As described in @sec:fcrit, at lower frequencies we expect there to
be features in the current that span the width of the observation
window, making it difficult to distinguish standing waves.
At higher frequencies, it is more likely that the standing waves
will be the only features that are coherent over the width of the
window.

Therefore strategy:

1. Use pre-front signal to identify the first few modes.

2. Use full signal to identify the remainder of the wavefield, using
   coherence of the waves to distinguish from remainder.



## Characteristics of standing waves

The horizontal and vertical velocity components due to standing waves
with surface amplitude $\eta$ are given by

$$
u = \frac{\pi \eta_k}{T} \left( \frac{\cosh kz}{\sinh kH} \right) \sin{kx}
\sin{\omega_k t}
$$

$$
w = \frac{\pi \eta_k}{T} \left( \frac{\sinh kz}{\sinh kH} \right) \cos{kx}
\sin{\omega_k t}
$$

We can see that the form of standing waves is dependent on the tank
geometry, the measurement location, the time since the initial
excitation and the projection of the initial excitation onto the
possible wave modes.

We will look at each of the horizontal, vertical and time components
in turn.


### Horizontal variation

The horizontal component of the standing wave velocity components is
given by

$$
\label{eq:sw-horizontal-u}
u(x) = \sin{kx}
$$

$$
\label{eq:sw-horizontal-w}
w(x) =  \cos{kx}
$$

With a non unity reflection coefficient (i.e. in reality) we expect
a different form for the horizontal variance of the waves. In
particular we do not expect nodes to go to zero.

...Equations with r!=1...


### Vertical profile

The vertical profile of the standing wave velocity components is
given by

$$
u(z) = \frac{\cosh kz}{\sinh kH}
$$

$$
w(z) = \frac{\sinh kz}{\sinh kH}
$$

Importantly, these profiles are dependent on the frequency of the
standing wave.

```{.python .input  n=15}
def vu(z, k, H=0.25):
    """Vertical profile of horizontal velocity component."""
    return np.cosh(k * z) / np.sinh(k * H)

def vw(z, k, H=0.25):
    """Vertical profile of vertical velocity component."""
    return np.sinh(k * z) / np.sinh(k * H)

def theoretical_vertical_profile(z, k, component='u', norm='max', H=0.25):
    """Compute the vertical profile for given z, k for
    given component of velocity (either 'u' or 'w'), and
    with optional normalisation to the max (default) or 
    mean of the profile or a scalar.
    
    k, z can be scalar or vector
    
    Returns the vertical profile over [z, k]
    """
    k = np.atleast_2d(k)
    z = np.atleast_2d(z).T
    
    if component == 'u':
        v = vu(z, k, H=H)
    elif component == 'w':
        v = vw(z, k, H=H)

    if norm == 'max':
        return v / v.max(axis=0, keepdims=True)
    elif norm == 'mean':
        return v / v.mean(axis=0, keepdims=True)
    elif type(norm) in (float, int):
        return v / norm
    else:
        return v
```

```{.python .input  n=18}
def create_k_interpolator(with_zero=True):
    """Create a lookup function that finds k as a function of
    frequency."""
    k = np.hstack(([0], np.logspace(-3, 4.5, 100)))
    return interp.interp1d(standing_frequency(k=k), k)

k_f = create_k_interpolator()

def create_vertical_profile(component='u', fmax=20, zmax=0.25, z=None, res=100, norm='max'):
    """For a given velocity component ('u', 'w'), create a function
    that returns the vertical profile of that component for given 
    z, f.
    """
    freqs = np.linspace(0, fmax, res)
    if z is None:
        z = np.linspace(0, zmax, res)

    # Can't actually evaluate vertical profile at f=0,
    # so remove this and tack on the limit (approaching 1 for u)
    profile = theoretical_vertical_profile(z=z, k=k_f(freqs[1:]), component=component, norm=norm)
    
    if component == 'u':
        limit = np.ones(z.size)
    elif component == 'w':
        limit = np.linspace(0, 1, z.size)
    
    profile = np.hstack((limit[:, None], profile))

    return interp.RectBivariateSpline(z, freqs, profile)

uprofile = create_vertical_profile('u', zmax=r.z.max(), norm='max')
wprofile = create_vertical_profile('w', zmax=r.z.max(), norm='max')
```

```{.python .input  n=21}
## fig:standing-vertical-profile
# Frequency dependence of the vertical profile of velocity for horizontal
# and vertical components, normalised to the maximum of the profile for
# each frequency.

freqs = np.linspace(0, 5, 100)
Z, F = np.meshgrid(r.z, freqs, indexing='ij')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True, figsize=(6, 6))
lvl = np.linspace(0, 1, 11)

c0 = ax[0].contourf(F, Z, uprofile(r.z, freqs), levels=lvl)
c1 = ax[1].contourf(F, Z, wprofile(r.z, freqs), levels=lvl)

fig.suptitle('')

ax[0].set_title('$u(f, z)$')
ax[1].set_title('$w(f, z)$')

ax[0].set_ylabel('height (m)')
ax[1].set_ylabel('height (m)')

ax[1].set_xlabel('frequency (Hz)')

ax[0].set_xlim(0, 5)
ax[1].set_xlim(0, 5)

fig.subplots_adjust(right=0.85)
cax = fig.add_axes([0.9, 0.35, 0.03, 0.3])
cbar = fig.colorbar(c0, cax=cax)
cbar.set_ticks([0, 0.5, 1]);
```

@fig:standing-vertical-profile shows the transition between the shallow and deep
water approximations. In extreme shallow water, the wave occupies the full
depth; in extreme deep water, the wave is confined to the surface.

This gives us an a priori idea of the frequency at which standing waves will
cease to be a problem throughout the fluid. Below 2Hz, the waves can be said
to affect the full fluid depth; above 5Hz, waves are clearly in the deep water
regime with energy confined to the surface. Unless the wave forming disturbance
has projected a lot of energy onto the higher frequency modes, the higher
frequency waves are only going to be visible in the surface layer.

### Time decay

Not shown in these equations, but there is dissipation and decay of
the wave amplitude.

This decay will be due to a non unity reflection coefficient at the
wall and also losses due to viscosity.

In general we expect the time decay to be a function of the fluid
viscosity, the standing wave speed and the length of the tank (to
account for the number of wall reflections).


## Estimating the waves


### Pre-front estimation

Fit successive peaks, minimising power spectrum, allowing for
exponential decay and using empirically determined f(x).
Could have done this in the time domain, but easier to reason with
in the frequency domain.

```{.python .input  n=23}
def find_nearest_idx(array,value):
    return (np.abs(array-value)).argmin()


def find_closest_peaks(power, freqs, guess_freqs):
    """Given a power spectrum over frequencies `freqs` 
    find the array indices of the power spectrum peaks 
    closest to the guess_freqs.
    """
    # find the maxima in the power spectrum
    maxima = sig.argrelextrema(power, np.greater)

    maxima_freqs = np.zeros(freqs.shape)
    maxima_freqs[maxima] = freqs[maxima]
    
    # determine the peaks as the closest maxima to each of the standing wave frequencies
    peak_indices = [find_nearest_idx(maxima_freqs, f) for f in guess_freqs]
    return peak_indices
    

def construct_wave(amplitude, f, time, decay=0):
    return (amplitude * np.exp(2j * np.pi * f * time) * np.exp(decay * time)).real

def wave_fft(amplitude, f, size, window, decay=0, dt=0.01):
    time = np.arange(window.size) * dt
    wave = (2 / window.sum()) * construct_wave(amplitude, f, time, decay=decay) * window
    return np.fft.rfft(wave, size)

def subtract_amplitude_fft(fft, amplitude, f, size, window, decay=0):
    return fft - wave_fft(amplitude, f, size, window, decay=decay)


def minimise_this_decay((amplitude_re, f, amplitude_im, decay), fft, size, window):
    amplitude = np.complex(amplitude_re, amplitude_im)
    return np.linalg.norm(subtract_amplitude_fft(fft, amplitude, f, size, window, decay=decay))


def minimise_power_decay(f, fft, freqs, size, window, bounds=None):
    power = np.abs(fft)
    peak = find_closest_peaks(power, np.array(freqs), guess_freqs=np.array([f]))
    idx = np.abs(freqs - f).argmin()
    
    idx = peak
    
    amplitude = power[idx]
    # get phase from the fft (assume it doesn't change)
    phase = np.angle(fft[idx])
    
    amplitude = fft[idx]
        
    if bounds is not None:
        damp = np.abs(amplitude) * 0.3
        bounds = [(amplitude.real - damp, amplitude.real + damp), 
                  bounds, 
                  (amplitude.imag - damp, amplitude.imag + damp), 
                  (-0.02, -0.002)]
    minim = opt.minimize(minimise_this_decay, 
                         #method='TNC', 
                         x0=(amplitude.real, freqs[peak], amplitude.imag, -0.007), 
                         args=(fft, size, window),
                         bounds=bounds)
                         
    opt_amplitude_re = minim.x[0]
    opt_freq = minim.x[1]
    opt_amplitude_im = minim.x[2]
    opt_decay = minim.x[3]
    
    camplitude = np.complex(opt_amplitude_re, opt_amplitude_im)
        
    return camplitude, opt_freq, opt_decay, wave_fft(camplitude, opt_freq, size, window, opt_decay)


def comb_frequencies_decay(fft, nf, window, size, df=0.01, plots=False):
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    
    amplitudes = np.zeros(nf, np.complex)
    frequencies = np.zeros(nf, np.float)
    decay = np.zeros(nf, np.float)
    peak_ffts = np.zeros((nf, freqs.size), np.complex)
    
    if plots:
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(fft), 'k', linewidth=3, alpha=0.5)
    # go through each guess frequency and find the nearest wave 
    # amplitude (complex) and frequency that would minimise the 
    # power spectrum, subtracting the optimal wave each time.
    for i, f in enumerate(standing_frequency(np.arange(1, nf + 1))):
        amplitudes[i], frequencies[i], decay[i], peak_ffts[i] = minimise_power_decay(f, fft, freqs, size, window, 
                                                                                     bounds=(f-df,f+df))
        fft = fft - peak_ffts[i]
        
        if plots:
            plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(peak_ffts[i]))
            plt.plot(frequencies[i], np.abs(amplitudes[i]), 'o')
            plt.annotate(round(decay[i], 4), 
                         xy=(frequencies[i], np.abs(amplitudes[i])), 
                         xytext=(frequencies[i] / (1.2 - 0.05), 1 - 0.1 * (i + 1)),
                         textcoords='axes fraction',
                         arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05))
            plt.xlim(0.05, 1.2)
            
    if plots:
        plt.plot(freqs, np.abs(fft))
        
    return amplitudes, frequencies.real, decay, peak_ffts



def extract_waves(data, nf, component='w', size=2**15, window='hanning', 
                  plots=False, length=8000, decay=True, 
                  dct_index=3, vertical=True, z=r.z):
    x = r.X[0, :, 0]
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    window = sig.get_window(window, data.shape[-1], fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(data * window, n=size, axis=-1)
    
    
    amplitudes, frequencies, tdecay, peak_ffts = comb_frequencies_decay(fft.mean(axis=0), nf=nf, window=window, size=size, plots=plots)

    iamp = interp.RectBivariateSpline(x, freqs, np.abs(fft))
    amplitude_variation = iamp(x, frequencies[:nf])
     
    if plots:
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(x, amplitude_variation, '--')
    
    dct = fftpack.dct(amplitude_variation, axis=0, norm='ortho')
    dct[dct_index:, :] = 0
    amplitude_variation = fftpack.idct(dct, axis=0, norm='ortho')
    
    if plots:
        plt.plot(x, amplitude_variation)
    
    # scale the amplitude variation to its mean
    amplitude_variation /= amplitude_variation.mean(axis=0)
    
    full_amplitudes = amplitude_variation * amplitudes[None, :]

    if not decay:
        tdecay = np.zeros(tdecay.size)
    
    time = np.arange(length) * 0.01
    
    # create waves with axes [z, x, t, k]
    # only varies over [x, t, k] at this point
    waves = (2 / window.sum()) * construct_wave(full_amplitudes[None, :, None, :], 
                                                frequencies[None, None, None, :nf], 
                                                time=time[None, None, :, None],
                                                decay=tdecay[None, None, None, :nf]).real
    
    if vertical:
        # compute vertical profile of computed frequencies 
        # and extend the waves over that profile
        profile = theoretical_vertical_profile(z, k_f(frequencies), norm='mean', component=component)
        return profile[:, None, None, :] * waves
    
    else:
        # remove the empty z axis, returning [x, t, k]
        return waves.squeeze()
```

```{.python .input  n=27}
## fig:pre-front-residual-power
# Power spectrum of the pre front signal showing the 
# original (blue) and residual signals.
# The residual is smaller when allowing the minimisation
# to minimise decay (red) than when not (green).
##

plt.figure()
plot_total_fft(presignal)
plot_total_fft(presignal - nodecay_waves[extractindex].mean(axis=0))
plot_total_fft(presignal - decay_waves[extractindex].mean(axis=0))
plt.ylim(0, 2)
plt.xlim(0.05, 1.2)

plt.xlabel('frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('amplitude');
```

```{.python .input  n=28}
## fig:pre-front-residual-power-2d
# Horizontal power spectra of (a) the pre-front signal;
# (b) the extracted wave signal; (c) the remaining signal.
##

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, sharex=True)
axes[0].set_title('(a) power of pre front signal')
c = contour_fft(presignal, ax=axes[0], xlim=(0, 2.5))

axes[1].set_title('(b) power of extracted waves')
contour_fft(decay_waves[extractindex], ax=axes[1], xlim=(0, 2.5))

axes[2].set_title('(c) remaining pre front signal')
contour_fft(presignal - decay_waves[extractindex], ax=axes[2], xlim=(0, 2.5))

fig.text(0.01, 0.5, 'Horizontal', va='center', rotation='vertical')

fig.tight_layout()
fig.subplots_adjust(left=0.1);
```

```{.python .input  n=29}
rsignal = r.U[..., 300:8300].mean(axis=0) - decay_waves
```

```{.python .input  n=30}
## fig:full-residual
# Hovmoller of the gravity current showing 
# (a) the signal with waves
# and (b) the signal with the leading standing wave
# modes subtracted. The higher order modes are still 
# clearly visible.
##

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True)

axes[0].contourf(r.T[0, ..., 300:8300], r.X[0, ..., 300:8300], r.U[..., 300:8300].mean(axis=0), 100);
axes[1].contourf(r.T[0, ..., 300:8300], r.X[0, ..., 300:8300], rsignal, 100);

axes[0].set_title('(a) Mean u over z')
axes[1].set_title('(b) Mean u over z, with leading waves subtracted')

axes[1].set_xlabel('time from lock release (s)')
fig.text(0.01, 0.5, 'Horizontal (m)', va='center', rotation='vertical')

fig.tight_layout()
fig.subplots_adjust(left=0.1);
```

```{.python .input  n=31}
## fig:full-residual-power
# The remaining full signal power after subtracting the leading
# order standing wave modes. (a) the mean power spectrum over
# x showing the original (blue) and residual (green) power;
# (b) the residual power spectrum over x.
##

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True)

axes[0].set_title('full  and residual signal mean power over x')
plot_total_fft(r.U[..., 300:8300].mean(axis=0), ax=axes[0], xlim=(0, 2.5), ylim=(0, 2.5))
plot_total_fft(rsignal, ax=axes[0], xlim=(0, 2.5), ylim=(0, 2.5))

axes[1].set_title('Power of remaining signal')
contour_fft(rsignal, ax=axes[1], xlim=(0, 2.5), levels=(0, 2.5));
```

### Full-signal estimation

Identifying the higher order modes is either very difficult or
impossible, due to the limits on peak resolution in the limited
pre-front signal (@sec:peak-isolation).

Here we determine the remainder of the wave field empirically.

#### Variance in x

Real standing waves do not follow the simple theoretical shape given
by [@eq:sw-horizontal-u; @eq:sw-horizontal-w].
The theoretial horizontal profile becomes difficult to estimate with
a viscous fluid and non unity reflection at the walls.
A data driven technique is needed to determine how the waves vary in
the horizontal.


##### Data decomposition

We wish to identify features that are coherent over $x$.
We know that the power of any given standing wave will vary in x.
We wish to approximate this variance.

Remember, due to the decay of the standing waves over time, we do
not know the theoretical form of the variance.
Further, the standing waves are superposed on the underlying data
that we wish to retrieve.

A first approximation to extracting such features is to take the mean over
the x-axis.
The result of doing this with our data is shown in
@fig:mean-waves(a): subtracting the mean will remove only the
invariant part of any standing wave's power.

The mean is the limit of a low pass filter - it is the DC component
of the signal.
We can better approximate the signal by including non-DC
components.
Recall that we are relying on the higher frequency standing waves to
be the *only* features in the data that are coherent over x.
As we use more higher order coefficients we expect to increasingly
include the underlying data in our approximation.

Consider the fourier transform over the x-axis of the horizontal
velocity component, as shown in @fig:dft-dct-data(a).
The energy representing the standing waves can be seen in the
pre-front region.
The 1st coefficient, the mean, holds the majority of the energy,
with alternate successive coefficients holding the remainder.
In the post-front region, the current energy is spread over a wide
range of coefficients.
This is the problem with the DFT: we cannot separate out the
standing wave signal from the current signal because both are spread
over a similar range of transform coefficients.
A good approximation of the standing waves with the DFT requires
that we do not truncate our transform very much; this is a problem
because we would very much like to truncate the region in which
there is appreciable energy coming from the current.

We can gain a better approximation than the Discrete Fourier
Transform by using the Discrete *Cosine* Transform (DCT).
In the DCT, we decompose the signal into a set of cosine modes
of the signal length.
The crucial difference between the DCT and the DFT is the boundary
conditions: periodic for the DFT, but *symmetric* for the DCT [^1].
The symmetric boundaries free the DCT to approximate generic signals
with far fewer coefficients than the DFT.
See @fig:dft-dct-ramp for a demonstration of this in the simple case
of a ramp: the DFT cannot make a good approximation to this signal
because of the constraints on it's boundaries, whereas the DCT can
make a good approximation even with only a single non-mean
coefficient.

@fig:dft-dct-data(b) shows the DCT as applied to our data.
Whereas the DFT in @fig:dft-dct-data(a) spreads energy out over odd
coefficients, the standing wave energy is compacted into the first
couple of coefficients.


[^1]: There is also a Discrete *Sine* Transform, which has
  *anti-symmetric* boundaries (i.e. an odd extension of the
  function). This is far less useful for approximating a generic
  coherent signal than the DCT (which has an even extension at the
  boundaries).

```{.python .input  n=32}
## fig:dft-dct-ramp
# Approximation of a ramp with the DFT and the DCT
##

def compare_dft_dct():
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2)

    x = np.linspace(-1, 1)
    y = np.linspace(-1, 1)
    #y = np.bartlett(50)

    axes[0].plot(x, y)
    axes[0].set_title('(a) Ramp signal and reconstruction')
    axes[0].set_ylabel('signal')
    axes[0].set_xlabel('coefficient')

    axes[1].set_title('(b) Transform coefficient power')
    axes[1].set_ylabel('magnitude')
    axes[1].set_xlabel('coefficient')

    dft = fftpack.rfft(y)
    axes[1].stem(np.abs(dft), 'g-', 'g.')
    dft[3:] = 0
    y_dft = fftpack.irfft(dft)

    dct = fftpack.dct(y, norm='ortho')
    axes[1].stem(np.abs(dct), 'r-', 'r.')
    dct[2:] = 0
    y_dct = fftpack.idct(dct, norm='ortho')

    axes[0].plot(x, y_dft)
    axes[0].plot(x, y_dct)
    
    #axes[1].set_yscale('log')
    
    fig.tight_layout()

compare_dft_dct()
```

```{.python .input  n=33}
def brickpass(signal, cutoff, high_cutoff=False, axis=-1):
    """Brick wall filter"""
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(signal.shape[axis], d=0.01)
    
    s = [slice(None) for _ in range(signal.ndim)]
    s[axis] = freqs < cutoff
    rfft = fft.copy()
    rfft[s] = 0
    
    if high_cutoff:
        s[axis] = freqs > high_cutoff
        rfft[s] = 0
        
    rdata = np.fft.irfft(rfft, axis=axis)
    return rdata

def butterpass(signal, cutoff, high_cutoff=False, axis=-1, order=2):
    """Butterworth filter in frequency domain"""
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(signal.shape[axis], d=0.01)
    
    s = [None for _ in range(signal.ndim)]
    s[axis] = slice(None)
    
    n = 2 * order
    
    if cutoff == 0:
        lo_butter = np.ones(freqs.size)
    else:
        lo_butter = 1 - (1 / (1 + (freqs / cutoff) ** n))
        
    if not high_cutoff:
        hi_butter = np.ones(freqs.size)
    else:
        hi_butter = (1 / (1 + (freqs / high_cutoff) ** n))

    rfft = fft * lo_butter[s] * hi_butter[s]
    rdata = np.fft.irfft(rfft, axis=axis)
    return rdata
```

```{.python .input  n=38}
## fig:dft-dct-data
# DFT and DCT of the full signal, showing the projection onto the
# transform coefficients as a function of time. The gravity current
# signal (in the POST-FRONT region) is projected similarly across
# both transforms. The standing wave signal (clearly visible in the
# PRE-FRONT region) is much more concentrated in the first few
# coefficients in the DCT than in the DFT. This is the 'energy
# compaction' property of the DCT.
##

def plot_dft_dct_comp_data(cutoff=0.6, upper=0.07, tstride=10):
    dct = fftpack.dct(brickpass(r.U[:].mean(axis=0), cutoff), axis=0) / 2
    dft = fftpack.rfft(brickpass(r.U[:].mean(axis=0), cutoff), axis=0)

    xf = np.fft.rfftfreq(r.x.size, d=np.diff(r.x)[0])
    xi = np.arange(xf.size) + 1
    XF, TF = np.meshgrid(xi, r.t, indexing='ij')
    where = np.s_[:20, 3000:6000:tstride]

    extent = (TF[where].min(), TF[where].max(), XF[where].min() - 0.5, XF[where].max() + 0.5)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize=(9, 6), sharex=True, sharey=True)

    im0 = ax[0].imshow(np.abs(dft[where]), extent=extent, aspect='auto', vmin=0, vmax=upper, interpolation='none', origin='lower left')
    im1 = ax[1].imshow(np.abs(dct[where]), extent=extent, aspect='auto', vmin=0, vmax=upper, interpolation='none', origin='lower left')

    for i in xi[where[0]]:
        ax[0].axhline(i - 0.5, color='w', alpha=0.4)
        ax[1].axhline(i - 0.5, color='w', alpha=0.4)

    fig.text(0.01, 0.5, 'Transform coefficient', va='center', rotation='vertical')

    ax[0].axvline(41, ymin=-1, ymax=1, color='r', linewidth=2, clip_on=False)
    ax[1].axvline(41, ymin=0, ymax=1, color='r', linewidth=2, clip_on=False)

    ax[0].text(40.0, 13, 'PRE-FRONT', color='w', fontsize=15, va='center', rotation='vertical')
    ax[0].text(41.5, 13, 'POST-FRONT', color='w', fontsize=15, va='center', rotation='vertical')

    ax[0].set_title('(a) DFT')
    ax[1].set_title('(b) DCT')
    ax[1].set_xlabel('time (s)')

    fig.tight_layout()
    
    fig.subplots_adjust(right=0.85, left=0.07)
    cax = fig.add_axes([0.9, 0.15, 0.03, 0.7])
    fig.colorbar(im0, cax=cax)


plot_dft_dct_comp_data()
```

##### Results

Applying the DCT to our data allows us to determine the standing
waves and their variance in the x-axis to a good level.
@fig:xvar-standing-waves shows the results of applying the mean, DFT
and DCT methods to our data. Clearly, the DCT is the best performer
in subtracting the waves.

```{.python .input  n=39}
def mean_waves(signal, axis=0):
    return signal.mean(axis=axis)

def fft_waves(signal, n=2):
    fft = fftpack.rfft(signal, axis=0)
    fft[n:, :] = 0
    return fftpack.irfft(fft, axis=0)

def dct_waves(signal, n=2, dct_type=2, axis=0, cutoff=0, bandpass=brickpass):
    if cutoff:
        signal = bandpass(signal, cutoff, axis=-1)
    dct = fftpack.dct(signal, axis=axis, type=dct_type, norm='ortho')
    where = [slice(None) for _ in dct.shape]
    where[axis] = slice(n, None)
    dct[where] = 0
    return fftpack.idct(dct, type=dct_type, axis=axis, norm='ortho')

import numpy.testing as npt

npt.assert_array_almost_equal(mean_waves(rsignal), fft_waves(rsignal, 1)[0], decimal=15)
npt.assert_array_almost_equal(mean_waves(rsignal), dct_waves(rsignal, 1)[0], decimal=15)
```

```{.python .input  n=41}
# Power spectra over (f, x):
# (a) The original data;
# (b) The remainder after subtracting the mean;
# (c) The remainder after subtracting a 2 component DFT;
# (d) The remainder after subtracting a 2 component DCT.
# Clearly, the DCT does the best job of removing the wave field.
##

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True, figsize=(8, 8))

contour_fft(rsignal, ax=axes[0, 0], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[0, 0].set_title('(a) original data')

contour_fft(rsignal - mean_waves(rsignal), ax=axes[1, 0], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[1, 0].set_title('(b) remainder mean')

contour_fft(np.tile(mean_waves(rsignal)[None], (r.x.size, 1)), ax=axes[1, 1], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[1, 1].set_title('estimation mean')

contour_fft(rsignal - fft_waves(rsignal, n=2), ax=axes[2, 0], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[2, 0].set_title('(c) remainder DFT')

contour_fft(fft_waves(rsignal), ax=axes[2, 1], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[2, 1].set_title('estimation DFT')

contour_fft(rsignal - dct_waves(rsignal, n=2), ax=axes[3, 0], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[3, 0].set_title('(d) remainder DCT')

contour_fft(dct_waves(rsignal), ax=axes[3, 1], xlim=(0.6, 2.5))
axes[3, 1].set_title('estimation DCT')

fig.tight_layout()

# have to call after tight_layout or confusion results
axes[0, 1].set_visible(False)
```

#### Variance in z

As discussed above, it is clear that the shallow water approximation
is invalid for the higher frequencies of the observed wave peaks.

```{.python .input  n=42}
## fig:pre-front-vertical-power
# Power spectrum of the horizontal component of the 
# pre-front signal over the vertical.
# The vertical profile clearly varies with frequency.
##

def z_fft(signal, mean=False, axis=-1, size=2**15, window='hanning', xlim=(0.05, 5), levels=(0, 2, 50)):
    window = sig.get_window(window, signal.shape[axis], fftbins=False)
    
    fft = np.fft.rfft(signal * window, size, axis=axis)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(size, d=0.01)
    
    lvl = np.linspace(*levels)
    Ff, Zf = np.meshgrid(freqs, r.z)

    which = (freqs > xlim[0]) & (freqs < xlim[1])
    F = Ff[:, which]
    Z = Zf[:, which]
    
    abs_fft = np.abs(fft).mean(axis=1)
    
    if mean:
        abs_fft /= abs_fft.mean(axis=0)
    
    plt.contourf(F, Z, abs_fft[:, which], levels=lvl)

plt.title('Power spectrum of pre-front signal as a function of height')
plt.xlabel('frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('height (m)')

z_fft(r.U[:, :, :3000], window='boxcar');
```

```{.python .input  n=43}
## fig: vertical-profile-frequency
# Theoretical profile of the horizontal velocity component,
# scaled to the velocity at the surface.
##

plt.title('Vertical profile of $u$ as a function of frequency')

plt.ylabel('Height (m)')
plt.xlabel('Magnitude of $u$ relative to surface amplitude')

zz = np.linspace(0, 0.25, 100)

for f in np.arange(1, 6):
    plt.semilogx(theoretical_vertical_profile(z=zz, k=k_f(f), norm='max'), zz, color='0.2')
    norm = theoretical_vertical_profile(z=0.25, k=k_f(f), norm='max')
    plt.text(theoretical_vertical_profile(z=0.03, k=k_f(f), norm=norm) * 2, 0.03, str(f) + ' Hz', bbox=dict(fc='0.8', ec='0.8'))

plt.axhspan(r.z.min(), r.z.max(), color='0.8')
plt.text(2e-8, 0.1, 'observed region')

plt.xlim(-11, 2)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_minor_locator(plt.FixedLocator([]))
plt.gca().invert_xaxis()
```

Clearly the wave energy becomes increasingly concentrated at the surface layer
as the frequency increases. Above 3Hz, we expect wave amplitudes $10^{-3}$ the
size of the surface amplitude.

This doesn't necessarily mean that these higher frequencies will be
insignificant in our signal: there could be a strong projection of the wave
forming disturbance onto higher frequencies. The power spectrum of the uppermost
layer of the observed region does not bear this out though [@fig:power-
uppermost] - frequency content drops off significantly above 3Hz.

```{.python .input  n=56}
## fig:power-uppermost
# Power spectrum of the uppermost region of the pre-front
# signal. Power drops off significantly above 2 Hz, suggesting
# that the standing wave contribution from high frequencies
# is negligible.
##

plt.title('power spectrum of uppermost region')

plot_smooth_fft(r.U[-1, :, :3000].mean(axis=0))

plt.xscale('linear')

plt.grid(axis='x', which='major', linestyle='-')

plt.xlim(0, 10)
plt.ylim(0.001, 2)
plt.yscale('log')

plt.xlabel('frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('amplitude (log scale)');
```

We need to approximate the vertical component. To do so we can use the
theoretical profile - it is robust under real conditions, unlike the
theoretical horizontal component.

The procedure is this: take the full signal (less the leading waves) and perform
the DCT technique above to maximise the standing wave to remainder signal ratio.
This gives us a wave signal in (x, t).

Now, transform into the frequency domain and multiply by the *theoretical*
vertical profile to obtain a wave signal in (z, x, f). Transforming back into
the time domain gives us a wave signal in (z, x, t).

```{.python .input  n=60}
def get_zxwaves(signal, component='u', cutoff=0.6, bandpass=brickpass, dt=0.01, flo=0.6, fhi=3):
    # create waves that capture the x variance from a mean over z
    xwaves = dct_waves(n=2, signal=signal.mean(axis=0), cutoff=cutoff, bandpass=bandpass)

    # transform to frequency domain
    xfft = np.fft.rfft(xwaves, axis=-1)
    freqs = np.fft.rfftfreq(xwaves.shape[-1], d=dt)

    # indices of frequency limits
    ihi = np.abs(freqs - fhi).argmin()
    ilo = np.abs(freqs - flo).argmin()
    
    # normalise to *mean* of vertical so that we can directly
    # multiply the fft (which comes from a vertical mean)
    vertical_profile = create_vertical_profile(component=component, fmax=20, z=r.z, res=500, norm='mean')
    
    # extend the fft uniformly over vertical
    zxfft = xfft[None, :, :] * np.ones((r.z.size, 1, 1))
    # scale the fft by the theoretical vertical profile, but only 
    # in frequency range that matters (don't want to scale the 
    # non-wave components that form the boundaries of the signal).
    # In principle we should care about the sharp edges here, but
    # it doesn't seem to have a significant effect.
    zxfft[:, :, ilo:ihi] = zxfft[:, :, ilo:ihi] * vertical_profile(r.z, freqs)[:, None, ilo:ihi]  # addresses todo below
        
    # transform back to time domain
    return np.fft.irfft(zxfft, axis=-1)

from functools import partial
rsignal = r.U[preindex] - decay_waves[..., :3000]
zxwaves = get_zxwaves(rsignal, bandpass=partial(butterpass, order=6), cutoff=0.45)
zxwaves_brick = get_zxwaves(rsignal, bandpass=brickpass, cutoff=0.45)
```

```{.python .input  n=61}
plt.contourf((rsignal - zxwaves - background[..., None])[:, :].mean(axis=1), levels=np.linspace(-0.0005, 0.0005))
```

```{.python .input  n=62}
plt.figure()

rbutter = (rsignal - zxwaves - background[..., None]).mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0)

plt.figure()
plot_smooth_fft(rbrick)

plt.xlim(0, 1)
plt.ylim(0, 0.05)
plt.xscale('linear');
```

This process has successfully removed the remaining waves from the signal. All
that remains are a ringing artefact and a background, varying over $(x, t)$.

The ringing originates from high-pass filtering the signal that is fed to the
DCT procedure. It is necessary to high-pass filter to avoid capturing x-variance
that comes from large scale features in the current: we use a high order (n=6)
butterworth filter. The scale of the ringing is shown in @fig:dct-ringing, along
with the ringing caused by a brick filter centered at the same frequency. Since
the ringing effect is small away from the edges and the interesting part of our
data is well centered in the time domain, we shall ignore this effect.

The background field is shown in @fig:piv-background, with the field computed
from the data remaining after wave removal and from the pre-removal data. Since
these fields differ only by a constant, the background cannot originate from the
processing described here. We attribute the background to the initial PIV
analysis and subtract it from the data.

```{.python .input  n=64}
## fig:piv-background

lvl = np.linspace(-0.003, 0.003, 30)


plt.contourf(background, levels=lvl)
plt.colorbar()

prebackground = (r.U[preindex].mean(axis=-1))

plt.figure()
plt.contourf(prebackground, levels=lvl)
plt.colorbar()

plt.figure()
plt.contourf(background - prebackground, levels=lvl)
plt.colorbar();
```

#### Variance in t

Since we derive the waves from the full timeseries, we do not need
to determine the decay of the waves as it is included in the
extracted signal.

#### Summary

Extract the w-waves as well.

```{.python .input  n=71}
presignal_w = r.W[preindex].mean(axis=0)

decay_waves_w = extract_waves(data=presignal_w, nf=4, component='w', window='hanning', plots=True, length=8000).sum(axis=-1)
```

## Validation

One big standing wave validation plot, showing 5 main runs, original
signal, power spectrum with detected peaks and subtracted power
spectrum, recovered signal.

Show effect of considering each of the different variances.

```{.python .input  n=77}
afp = np.abs(np.fft.rfft(r.U[..., 3300:8300], axis=-1)).mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0)
fp = np.abs(np.fft.rfft(su[..., 3000:], axis=-1)).mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0)
pfp = np.abs(np.fft.rfft(su[..., :3000], axis=-1)).mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0)

ff = np.fft.rfftfreq(5000, d=0.01)
pf = np.fft.rfftfreq(3000, d=0.01)
```

```{.python .input  n=78}
plt.plot(ff, fp)
plt.plot(ff, afp)

plt.plot(pf, pfp)

plt.xlim(0.05, 50)
#plt.xlim(1.5, 3)

plt.ylim(0.01, 5)

#plt.plot([1e-1, 1e1], [1e1, 0.33e-1])

plt.yscale('log')
plt.xscale('log')
```

```{.python .input  n=81}
def get_waves(run, component='u'):
    preindex = np.s_[..., :3000]
    
    velocity = getattr(r, component.upper())
    
    pre_front = velocity[preindex].mean(axis=0)

    pre_waves = extract_waves(data=pre_front, nf=4, component=component, 
                              window='hanning', plots=True, length=8000).sum(axis=-1)
    
    
    prewaveless = velocity[..., :8000] - pre_waves[..., :8000]
    
    zxwaves = get_zxwaves(prewaveless, component=component, cutoff=0.45, bandpass=partial(butterpass, order=6))
    
    background = (prewaveless - zxwaves)[..., :3000].mean(axis=-1)
    
    return pre_waves + zxwaves + background[..., None]
```
